#X text 645 268 <-- Frequency Modulated signal;
#X text 659 189 <-- modulating signal;
#X text 27 19 As we've seen in other topics \, in general \, modulating a signal means applying any changes to it. In this context \, we're talking about a modulating signal that controls a paramete \, such as Frequency \, our current topic. More precisely \, we're taling about "fast" modulation like we've seen in the last chapter with the Amplitude Modulation examples., f 67;
#X text 27 117 Let's check now the basic structure of Frequency Modulation. The signal to be modulated is called the "Carrier" - in FM synthesis \, this is also known as "Carrier Frequency". We also have a Modulator frequency \, which is the frequency of the modulating oscillator. Yes \, the modulating signal is usually an oscillator. The frequency deviation is controlled by the oscillator's amplitude and is also usually called "modulation index" \, but this is theoretically inaccurate. We'll see later how the index is actually the ratio between deviation and modulating frequency and how that relates to the way that modulation index behaves in Phase Modulation. What we need to know now is that modulation index here actually means 'frequency deviation amplitude'., f 67;
#X text 27 299 The frequency modulation procedure is simple. We just need to add the carrier signal to the modulating signal. Let's check the example to the right. By default \, we have a 400 Hz carrier signal \, a low frequency of 1 as the modulating frequency and an index of 100 - this means the modulating signal oscillates between -100 and 100 at every second \, so the resulting frequency modulating signal varies from 300 to 500 hz. Low frequency modulations generate vibrato or glissando like effects \, but try higher frequencies \, which is what FM synthesis is actually about. We'll see what happens in detail soon., f 67;
#X connect 0 0 7 0;
#X connect 1 0 6 0;
#X connect 2 0 3 0;
#X connect 3 0 0 1;
#X connect 4 0 2 0;
#X connect 5 0 11 0;
#X connect 6 0 0 0;
#X connect 7 0 8 0;
#X connect 11 0 3 1;
